        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-02-19 15:35:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/79b0508c-7aa4-11e2-b5c8-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  2 tests failed: replay-ost-single, sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "e07ead2691290b8fe7ca08fba291d718f1855989",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-19 21:50:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nBruno, please be careful not to push new versions of patches like that. It can cause more work for the owner.\n\nFor example, in this instance, patch-set 1 passed Maloo but patch-set 2 didn't. The failure probably isn't due to this change, but now we must determine why it failed and then try and retest this patch until it passes. Unfortunately this can drag on the landing process unnecessarily.\n\nIf you need to base your work on a pending patch, I suggest you \"checkout\" the dependency and base your work on that. Rather than \"cherry-picking\" the pending patch onto a different branch. This will allow you to \"git push\" without affecting the other, unmodified, dependent patches.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
